Boil a large #pot{} of water for the udon noodles.

Add the @udon noodles{300%g} and @fish sauce{to taste} then lower heat to medium-high
and cook until warmed through, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and pop back in the pot, off the heat.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste} and stir through to prevent sticking.

> TIP: If you're in a hurry you can boil the water in your kettle.

Halve, peel and chop the @shallot{1}(halved, peeled and chopped) into small pieces.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped).

Zest, then cut @lime{1}(zested and quartered) into quarters.

Halve the @baby corn{150%g}(halved lengthways) lengthways.

Place a large pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of oil.

When hot, add the baby corn.

Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Transfer to a #plate{} and set aside.

Add another drizzle of @oil{to taste} to the pan, if necessary.

Add the shallot and @garlic, ginger & lemongrass paste{1%sachet}. Cook, stirring,
until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add the @Irish pork mince{250%g}. IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after
handling raw mince.

Fry, breaking up pork into smaller pieces, until cooked through, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the @gochujang paste{1%sachet} (use less if you don't like spice) and cook,
stirring often, until the pork is browned, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in lime zest, @ketjap manis{1%sachet}, baby corn and @water{75%ml}.

Cook until baby corn is warmed through, ~{1%minute}.

Remove from the heat and stir through the @honey{1%sachet}. Add a splash of
water if you feel the sauce is too thick.

Add the drained noodles to the sauce and toss to coat.

Divide your fragrant pork noodles between plates.

Squeeze over a little lime juice to taste and serve remaining lime wedges on the
side.

Finish with a sprinkling of coriander.